Abstract¶

Our motivation for this project stems from identifying factors that lead to successful passing plays in the NFL. Specifically, we will be examining which route combinations are most effective in general, and which route combinations are most effective against specifc coverage schemes, how different passing nuances, such as drop type and RPO (run-pass option) impact a play's level of success, which route combinations are most likely to be interceptedand what other factors lead to an interception, and which coverage schemes are most effective against specific route combinations. The questions are addressed through a variety of machine learning models. We found that the combination of Curl, Curl, Go, Out and Swing routes were more successful than all other route combinations. We also saw that trick plays improve the odds of success in terms of drop back models, but this could be due to how infrequently trick plays are run. When analyzing defensive coverages, the defensive coverage scheme of Cover 3 was most effective against the route combination of Dig, Drag, Go and Post routes. The screen coverage scheme was also seen to be effective against a variety of route combinations. When examining the classification of interceptions on plays, Yard line, Presure on Play and Time Left (in the game) were the most influential factors. Additionally, Flat, Corner, and Go routes were the most influential passing routes and Cover 0, Cover 2, and Cover 3 were the most influential coverage schemes.

1. Introduction¶

Overall, our goal of the project was to evaluate and identify what the most effective passing strategies in the NFL are. This included evaluating different route concepts and coverage schemes to see which offer the highest expected value for an offense as well as how different factors influence the outcome of a play.

These results could help NFL teams optimize their passing-game strategy while providing some insights into different ways to leverage unique schemes and coverages. In the end, there are four key research questions that we hope to answer through different machine learning techniques:

  1. Which route combinations are most effective? Which route combinations are most effective against specific coverage schemes?
  2. Do different passing nuances (i.e., drop type, RPO) significantly impact a plays level of success?
  3. Which route (or route combinations) are most likely to be intercepted? What factors are most likely to lead to an interception?
  4. Which coverage schemes are most effective on defense? Which coverage schemes are most effective against specific route combinations?

Before answering those questions, we set out to explore our data and will provide some foundational knowledge on the dataset that we used.

Our data can be broken up into several types

Play Descriptors

  • Columns for where the play occurred and what teams were part of the play
  • Yards to go, Down, Location on Field, Offensive/Defensive Teams, Time in Qtr, etc.

Play Type

  • Routes Run, Drop back type, Defensive Coverage, etc

Play Results

  • First Down or Touchdown, yards gained, turnover, etc.

Calculated Columns

  • Measures of Success, Route Combination

Since one of our primary research questions is focused on route combinations (and not just individual routes), it made sense to consolidate the routes into fewer route types so that we had fewer unique route combinations (and ultimately lowering our sample size for route combinations). Below is the conversion we did for each of the different route types.

The next step in our data cleaning was to count the number of occurances for each route type for each play and convert the counts into columns.

In [8]:
pbp['KEY'] = pbp['GameID'].astype(str) + '-' + pbp['EventID'].astype(str)
full['KEY'] = full['GameID'].astype(str) + '-' + full['EventID'].astype(str)
play_routes = full.set_index(['KEY'])['Route'].str.get_dummies().sum(level=0).reset_index()

number_routes = full.groupby(['GameID','EventID']).size()
number_routes = number_routes.to_frame(name = 'count_routes').reset_index()
number_routes['KEY'] = number_routes['GameID'].astype(str) + '-' + number_routes['EventID'].astype(str)
#number_routes.head()

After getting the counts of each route by play, we merged these new columns back into the play data to get the number of each route along with the original play data. We then addded some additional columns such as a definition of success and the Yardline.

In [9]:
route_combo = pbp.merge(play_routes, on=['KEY'])
route_combo = route_combo[route_combo['EventType'] == 'pass']
route_combo = route_combo.merge(number_routes, on=['KEY'])
route_combo['success'] = np.where(route_combo['EPA'] >= 0, 1, 0)
route_combo['Yardline'] = np.where(route_combo['SideOfField'] == "Own", 100-route_combo['StartYard'], route_combo['StartYard'])

We then simplified the drop type as well using a similar process as the routes.

Based on the results of the correlation plot, we note a couple of observations:

  1. OffensiveYardage, Completion, and FirstDown are highly correlated with success, which makes sense given those are big factors in the calculation for EPA (which success is based off of).
  2. Higher number of routes (count_routes) and Down are positive indicators of a play using Shotgun.
  3. There are very few negatively correlated variables (aside from SackOnPlay and Attempt) and those that are negatively correlated are relatively weak.

The chart below shows the distribution of Dropback Types by whether a play was a success or not. We see that there is a relative consistent distribution between classes with successes having less than not. The one exception being Trick and Spike which don't have the same distributions but also don't make up as many of the plays.

3. Machine Learning¶

Expected Success Model with Gradient Boosting¶

One machine learning technique that we will utilize is the implementation of a Gradient Boosted logistic regression model. We built this model in order to create an "Expected Success" metric. With this, we can calculate the success rate of various route combinations and then calculate the expected success rate of those same route combinations. The difference between these two success rates will be "Success Rate Over Expected," which will be our primary method of answering research question number one.

The first step in building this model is to isolate the specific variables that we want to use. There are some variables (PlayDesc, GameID, PlayID, etc.) that are purely descriptive and so we can immediately eliminate them. Also, in order to make our data readable, we must remove observations in which an NA value exists.

Success based on Dropback Type¶

We are using a decision tree, a logistic regression, and SVC model for the classification route of success. By looking at node splits and coefficients, we can see if any of the dropback types provide significance for determining if a play will be successful or not.

Based on the data exploration, we include balanced as a class weight parameter since our classes are clearly unbalanced.

We created a function to aid in evaluating the models. This function provides the confusion matrix and other key model stats for classification models

In [27]:
def eval_model(pred, actual):
    '''
    Input: Model Predictions, Actual Values
    Output: Classification Metrics based on inputs

    Takes list of predictions and actuals to compute basic performance stats of a model
    '''
    conf_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_true = actual, y_pred = pred)

    #Recall
    recall = metrics.recall_score(y_true = actual, y_pred = pred)

    #Specificity
    specificity = conf_matrix[1][1] / (conf_matrix[0][1] + conf_matrix[1][1])

    #Precsion
    precision = metrics.precision_score(y_true = actual, y_pred = pred)


    #F1
    f1 = metrics.f1_score(y_true = actual, y_pred = pred)

    # Balanced Accuracy
    balanced = balanced_accuracy_score(actual, pred)
    
    return conf_matrix, recall, specificity, precision, balanced, f1

Defensive success based on coverage schemes¶

A logistic regression model and SVC models were used to identify the success rate of coverage schemes against different types of routes and route combinations. Also, the model will be able to identify and predict the optimal coverage scheme based on the route combinations. For this learning model, we will be reconstructing the target variable to focus on defensive stoppage and success. By doing so, we inverted the success target from our expected success model.

We also dropped additional variables that might interfere with the integrity of the model or indicate a successful stoppage by the defense (i.e., Fumble, Turnover, Interception, EPA, Offensive Yardage, etc.). For example, EPA is a formula that calculated the play's expected point added. If the play has a positive EPA, it is more likely to indicate the play was a success and the offensive strategy overbear the defense. These variables indirectly indicated the outcome of the play, which as a result, the model can directly predict the target without examining the route combinations.

4. Research Question Results¶

Expected Success Rate Evaluation¶

Once we had the expected success model built, we could go ahead and measure which route combinations were best. To do this, we created a "Success Rate Over Expected" metric, which takes the difference between the Success Rate (the percent of plays in which a specific route combination was deemed a 'success') and the Expected Success Rate (the average probability of successful plays based on the gradient boosted model).

In [63]:
# create a route combination column for each observation
for index, row in expected_success_df.iterrows():
    temp_str = ''

    angle = row['Angle'] * 'Angle, '
    comeback = row['Comeback'] * 'Comeback, '
    corner = row['Corner'] * 'Corner, '
    curl = row['Curl'] * 'Curl, '
    dig = row['Dig'] * 'Dig, '
    drag = row['Drag'] * 'Drag, '
    flat = row['Flat'] * 'Flat, '
    go = row['Go'] * 'Go, '
    other = row['Other'] * 'Other, '
    out = row['Out'] * 'Out, '
    post = row['Post'] * 'Post, '
    screen = row['Screen'] * 'Screen, '
    slant = row['Slant'] * 'Slant, '
    swing = row['Swing'] * 'Swing, '
    
    temp_str = str(angle + comeback + corner + curl + dig + drag + flat + go + other + out + post + screen + slant + swing)
    temp_str = temp_str[:-2]
    expected_success_df.at[index, 'route_combo'] = temp_str
In [64]:
# get the success rates and expected success rates and the counts of each route combo
success_means = expected_success_df.groupby('route_combo', as_index=False)['success', 'xp_success'].mean()
route_counts = expected_success_df.groupby('route_combo', as_index=False).size()
# join the two dataframes created
sroe_df = pd.concat([success_means, route_counts], axis = 1)
sroe_df = sroe_df.loc[:,~sroe_df.columns.duplicated()]
# rename the columns to be more accurate and convert them to percentages
sroe_df = sroe_df.rename(columns = {"success" : "success_rate", "xp_success" : "exp_success_rate"})
sroe_df['success_rate'] = round(sroe_df['success_rate']*100, 1)
sroe_df['exp_success_rate'] = round(sroe_df['exp_success_rate']*100, 1)
# calculate the success rate over expected (SROE)
sroe_df['sroe'] = sroe_df['success_rate'] - sroe_df['exp_success_rate']

# filter on route combinations with a minimum of 20 plays
sroe_final = sroe_df.loc[sroe_df['size'] >= 20]
sroe_final.sort_values('sroe', ascending = False).head()

Dropback Success Rates¶

Testing dropback type has shown some results in which type is more successful. We see Trick plays performing very weel compared to RPOs but they occur less frequent so may not be siginificant. However, when looking at the RPO vs standard stepback, the standard plays seem to perform better in isolation.

Continued experiments into models focused on dropback type and success will show if individual types hold any significance for influencing success rate.

In [101]:
def print_results(results):
    print('BEST PARAMS: {}\n'.format(results.best_params_))

    means = results.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
    stds = results.cv_results_['std_test_score']
    for mean, std, params in zip(means, stds, results.cv_results_['params']):

Classification Results¶

After performing the three different classifiers with oversampling to address class imbalance, the random forest model performed the best out of the three classifiers. The random forest classifier only misclassified 94 values our of over 9,000 values while the adaboost classifier misclassified a little over 120 values and the decision tree classifier misclassified over 200 values. Once grid searched were applied to each of the 3 models, and tuning was performed, The Adaboost Classifier performed better than the other two models.

The most influential features for the classification with all variables were Throw Depth, Yardline, Curl and Down.

When performing classifcation with route combination and coverage variables the random forest classifier out performed the other two classifiers. The random forest classifier misclassified 93 cases, which is less than the other two classifiers. The most influential route combinations are Go, Curl and Post routes. The most influential coverage schemes are Cover 1, Cover 3, and Cover 4.

This result shows that classification could be used to determine which situations could result in an interception, however over or under sampling would likely be necessary to address class imbalance issues, as it is much more likely an interception does not occur on a play.

for index, row in defense_success_df.iterrows():
    temp_str = ''

    angle = row['Angle'] * 'Angle, '
    comeback = row['Comeback'] * 'Comeback, '
    corner = row['Corner'] * 'Corner, '
    curl = row['Curl'] * 'Curl, '
    dig = row['Dig'] * 'Dig, '
    drag = row['Drag'] * 'Drag, '
    flat = row['Flat'] * 'Flat, '
    go = row['Go'] * 'Go, '
    other = row['Other'] * 'Other, '
    out = row['Out'] * 'Out, '
    post = row['Post'] * 'Post, '
    screen = row['Screen'] * 'Screen, '
    slant = row['Slant'] * 'Slant, '
    
    temp_str = str(angle + comeback + corner + curl + dig + drag + flat + go + other + out + post + screen + slant)
    temp_str = temp_str[:-2]
    defense_success_df.at[index, 'route_combo'] = temp_str

    DefensiveSuccess_means = defense_success_df.groupby(['route_combo', 'CoverageScheme'], as_index=False)['DefensiveSuccess'].mean()
    defensive_route_counts = defense_success_df.groupby(['route_combo', 'CoverageScheme'], as_index=False).size()
    defensiveSuccess_df = pd.concat([DefensiveSuccess_means, defensive_route_counts], axis = 1)
    defensiveSuccess_df = defensiveSuccess_df.loc[:,~defensiveSuccess_df.columns.duplicated()]
    
    defensiveSuccess_df['DefensiveSuccess'] = round(defensiveSuccess_df['DefensiveSuccess']*100, 1)
    # filter on route combinations with a minimum of 20 plays
    defensive_final_df = defensiveSuccess_df.loc[defensiveSuccess_df['size'] >= 20]
    defensive_final_df.sort_values('DefensiveSuccess', ascending = False).head(10)

plt.show()

The confusion matrix of the SVC multi-class indicated that all cover schemes with a small sample size were miss classified and classified between Cover 1 and Cover 3. With this new information, we can assume that Cover 1 and Cover 3 are distinctive, while the other cover schemes are derived from the two classes. Thus, the next step is to covert other cover schemes into Cover 1 or Cover 3 based on their similarity.

The confusion matrix of the SVC reduced multi-class indicated that Cover 1 and Cover 3 remain an issue for the miss classification. It indicated that cover schemes might have more similarities. Combining multiple cover classes into one would lead to heavily skewed toward the cover class with the most sample. With this new information, we will need to introduce more variables that can describe the function of different types of cover coverage schemes.

5. Conclusions¶

Answering the research questions¶

For our research questions, we were able to provide some insights using the route combos and the defensive coverages. Other variables didn't show as much significance however the findings from the analysis are still useful nonetheless.

  1. We found that the most effective route combination was the Curl, Curl, Go, Out, Swing. This route combination opens up space by sending one receiver deep and providing different length of passes to seperate the defense. The swing part of the route gives the QB a checkdown in case of pressure.

We also found that the Corner, Drag, Post was specifically effective against the Cover 3 defense. The routes send 2 players behind the inital zone and 1 on the inside of the zone. If the 2 deeper routes are covered, there is an opportunity for the QB to still get the ball upfield and into a receiver's hands.

  1. Dropback type didn't have an impact on whether or not a play was successful. While this doesn't help provide insights on how to better call plays, it can help decision makers know they can play calls based on their playger strengths and it shouldn't have a negative impact. For example, a QB that is more athletic may benefit from a RPO compared to the standard stepback and that decision alone doesn't determine if the play will be successful.
  1. When looking at the defensive coverages, we found that Cover 0, 2, and 3 were the most influential in determining success. Defensive coordinators can benefit from this knowledge since they can better plan for a game. Cover 2 can result in double coverages with a corner covering a WR with help from the Safety over the top. This allows a CB to be more aggressive which can lead to more interceptions.
  1. The most efficient coverages were Screen and Cover 1. Screen plays are often used to exploit the defense being further back in coverage to allow time for blockers to get into position. However, if the defense is in a screen defense, the plays don't have time to setup and can be stopped early or cause turnovers.

Additional Opportunities¶

With additional time, we could have looked closer at play combinations, i.e an offense running 2 pass plays before a run or running the ball before a play action play to see if the conventional wisedom upholds or if defenses are getting smarter.

We could also look into individual players and how they performed given specific variables (i.e. are certain QBs better at RPO than others).
